          "type": "reasoning",
          "text": "The user is asking about the difference between `std::string&` (reference) vs `std::string*` (pointer) in C++, using the analogy of C's `char*`. Let me explain the idiomatic C++ approach.\n\nThe specific context: in C `trim_string` uses `char* s` (pointer), but in C++ `trim_str` uses `std::string& s` (reference). The user is wondering why reference instead of pointer.\n\nThis is about C++ idioms:\n\n1. **Pass by value** (`std::string s`) — copies the whole string. Expensive.\n2. **Pass by pointer** (`std::string* s`) — C-style, need to check for nullptr, use `->` syntax.\n3. **Pass by reference** (`std::string& s`) — no copy, cannot be null, no need to check. The caller passes it as if by value (`trim_str(temp)`), but the function modifies the original.\n\nIn C++:\n- Use references when the parameter must exist and you want to modify it.\n- Use pointers when the parameter can be null (optional) or when you need pointer arithmetic (arrays).\n\nFor `trim_str`, the string must exist (no null case), and we modify it in place. Reference is idiomatic C++ — the caller writes `trim_str(temp)` which is cleaner than `trim_str(&temp)` (pointer).",
